ğŸ§© 1. What is an Interface?

ğŸ‘‰ Definition:
An interface in Java is a blueprint of a class that defines a contract
(i.e., a set of methods) that implementing classes must follow.

It is used to achieve:
âœ…100% abstraction
âœ…Multiple inheritance
âœ…Loose coupling
âœ…Common behavior define karna across different classes.

ğŸ‘‰ In simple terms:

Interface tells â€œwhat to doâ€, not â€œhow to doâ€.

ğŸ§± 3. Syntax and Rules of Interface
âœ… Syntax:

interface InterfaceName {
    // implicitly public abstract methods
    void method1();
    void method2();
}

âœ… Implementation:
class ClassName implements InterfaceName {
    public void method1() { ... }
    public void method2() { ... }
}

âœ… Rules:
1. All methods are public and abstract by default.
2. Variables in interface are public static final by default.
3. You cannot create object of an interface.
4. A class implements an interface, not extends it.
5. An interface can extend another interface, but cannot extend a class.
6. A class can implement multiple interfaces.


ğŸ§© 8. Marker Interface

ğŸ‘‰ Interface with no methods and no fields.
Used to mark or tag a class for special behavior.

Examples in Java:

    # Serializable
    # Cloneable
    # Remote

interface Marker {}

class MyClass implements Marker {
    // just tagged
}

âš™ï¸ 9. Functional Interface (Java 8+)

Interface with exactly one abstract method.

@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b);
}


âœ… Used in Lambda Expressions:

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calculator c = (a, b) -> a + b;  // Lambda
        System.out.println(c.add(5, 10));
    }
}


Common functional interfaces in java.util.function:

    # Predicate<T>
    # Function<T,R>
    # Supplier<T>
    # Consumer<T>

âš™ï¸ 10. Nested Interface

Interface defined inside another class or interface.

class Outer {
    interface Inner {
        void display();
    }
}

class Demo implements Outer.Inner {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Nested Interface Example");
    }
}



ğŸ¯ Top INTERVIEW QUESTIONS

ğŸ”¹ Q1: Can an interface have a constructor?
Ans: âŒ No, because we cannot create objects of an interface.

ğŸ”¹ Q2: Can interface extend another interface?
Ans: âœ… Yes, and it can extend multiple interfaces.
interface A {}
interface B extends A {}

ğŸ”¹ Q3: Can a class implement multiple interfaces?
Ans: âœ… Yes â€” this enables multiple inheritance.

ğŸ”¹ Q4: Can an interface have a main() method?
Ans: âœ… Yes (since Java 8) because static methods are allowed.

ğŸ”¹ Q5: What is the difference between abstract class and interface?
Ans:
Abstract class: partial abstraction, single inheritance
Interface: full abstraction, multiple inheritance

ğŸ”¹ Q6: Can interface contain variables?
Ans: âœ… Yes, but they are public static final constants.

ğŸ”¹ Q7: What happens if two interfaces have same default method?
Ans: Class must override it to resolve ambiguity.

interface A { default void show() { System.out.println("A"); } }
interface B { default void show() { System.out.println("B"); } }

class C implements A, B {
    public void show() {
        A.super.show(); // or custom logic
    }
}

ğŸ”¹ Q9: Can an interface implement another interface?
Ans: âŒ No, only extend is allowed, not implement.

ğŸ”¹ Q10: What is a functional interface? Example?
Ans:
An interface with only one abstract method, used in Lambda expressions.
Example: Runnable, Comparable, or user-defined with @FunctionalInterface.




ğŸ§­ What comes inside Interface

1ï¸âƒ£ Abstract Methods
By default, interface ke sare methods public aur abstract hote hain.

interface Animal {
    void sound();   // public and abstract by default
    void eat();
}
ğŸ‘‰ Implement karne wali class ko sab methods override karne padte hain.

2ï¸âƒ£ Constants (Variables)

Inside Interface we can write variables, but wo automatically public, static, final hote hain.

interface Config {
    int MAX_USERS = 100;   // public static final by default
}

System.out.println(Config.MAX_USERS);

3ï¸âƒ£ Static Methods (Java 8+)
interface MathUtils {
    static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}
âœ… Access:
System.out.println(MathUtils.add(5, 10)); // 15

ğŸ¯ INTERVIEW QUESTIONS on This Topic
Q1. What members can an interface contain?
Abstract methods, constants, static methods, default methods,
private methods, nested types (interfaces/classes/enums/records).

Q2. Can interface have constructor?
âŒ No, because it cannot be instantiated.

Q3. Can interface have main() method?
âœ… Yes, since static methods are allowed.

Q4. Are variables inside interface always final?
âœ… Yes, they are public static final by default.

Q5. Can interface contain private method?
âœ… Yes, from Java 9 onward â€” used internally for code reuse.


